n.  Indian Shanti, Harendra.","Indian (Uttar Pradesh): Brahmin name, from Sanskrit <i>om</i>, the Hindu sacred and mystic syllable uttered at the beginning of prayers.","Cambodian: written ឱម, corresponding to the exclamation of solemn affirmation, of Sanskrit origin (see 1 above), chanted by Buddhist monks."],"variants":[{"name":"Oum","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Southeast Asian Heang, Hye, Kam, Kan, Kheng, Khin, Kun, Sang, Sok, Phong, Yom, Yoo, Youn, Cuong, Phal, Samnang, Tin.  Cambodian Sokha, Chheang, Choeun, Moeun, Roeun, Sambath, Samoeun, Savuth, Soeun, Sopheap.","Cambodian: written អ៊ុំ, from a Khmer word denoting an elder sibling of one's parent (i.e. ‘uncle’ or ‘aunt’). Compare   Om   3 and   Um   2."]}]},{"name":"Stapleton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Irish: habitational name from any of various places called Stapleton (in Devon, Gloucestershire, Somerset, Herefordshire, Shropshire, Leicestershire, North Yorkshire, Yorkshire, Cumberland), all named in Old English with <i>stapol</i> ‘post, pillar’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. The name is common in Ireland, where it has been established since medieval times in the counties of Tipperary and Kilkenny."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Geoffrey","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Germanic (Frankish and Lombard) origin, introduced to Britain by the Normans. It was in regular use among the counts of Anjou, ancestors of the English royal house of Plantagenet, who were descended from Geoffrey Plantagenet, Count of Anjou (  1113–51 ). It was a particularly popular name in England and France in the later Middle Ages; notable bearers in England include the poet  Geoffrey Chaucer  (  <i>c.</i>1340–1400 ) and in Wales the chronicler  Geoffrey  of Monmouth (  d. 1155 ). The original form and meaning of the name is disputed. According to one theory, it is merely a variant of   Godfrey ;  others derive the first part from the Germanic word <i>gawia</i> ‘territory’, <i>walah</i> ‘stranger’, or <i>gisil</i> ‘pledge’. Medieval forms can be found to support all these theories, and it is possible that several names have fallen together, or that the name was subjected to reanalysis by folk etymology at an early date."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Geoffrey of Stapleton was born about 1150, in Stapleton, Yorkshire, England. He had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. He died before about 1204."},"et":{"abt 1150–before about 1204":"umbes 1150–umbes enne 1204","1179–Male":"1179–Surnud","1193–Male":"1193–Surnud","1195–Female":"1195–Surnud","1150–1204":"1150–1204","1204":"1204","before about 1204":"umbes enne 1204","1179":"1179","abt 1150":"umbes 1150","1195":"1195","1150":"1150","1193":"1193","Stapleton, Yorkshire, England":"Stapleton, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"abt 1150–before about 1204":"noin 1150–ennen vuotta noin 1204","1179–Male":"1179–Kuollut","1193–Male":"1193–Kuollut","1195–Female":"1195–Kuollut","1150–1204":"1150–1204","1204":"1204","before about 1204":"ennen vuotta noin 1204","1179":"1179","abt 1150":"noin 1150","1195":"1195","1150":"1150","1193":"1193","Stapleton, Yorkshire, England":"Stapleton, Yorkshire, England"},"fr":{"abt 1150–before about 1204":"environ 1150–avant environ 1204","1179–Male":"1179–Décédé","1193–Male":"1193–Décédé","1195–Female":"1195–Décédée","1150–1204":"1150–1204","1204":"1204","before about 1204":"avant environ 1204","1179":"1179","abt 1150":"environ 1150","1195":"1195","1150":"1150","1193":"1193","Stapleton, Yorkshire, England":"Stapleton, Everwyck, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Geoffrey of Stapleton est né environ 1150, à Stapleton, Everwyck, Angleterre. Il a eu au moins 2 fils et 1 fille. Il est décédé avant environ 1204."},"de":{"abt 1150–before about 1204":"um 1150–vor um 1204","1179–Male":"1179–Verstorben","1193–Male":"1193–Verstorben","1195–Female":"1195–Verstorben"